1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:03,090
Speaker 14: Hello, everyone,
and thank you for listening.

2
00:00:03,590 --> 00:00:08,530
Today, I want to talk about a topic that
many organizations are actively exploring.

3
00:00:09,230 --> 00:00:16,150
How do we move beyond AI experimentation
and successfully deploy LLM-powered

4
00:00:16,170 --> 00:00:18,510
agents in production environment?

5
00:00:19,129 --> 00:00:25,989
The title of the session is LLM Agents
as Copilots for Scalable Decision

6
00:00:25,989 --> 00:00:28,240
Systems in Production Environments.

7
00:00:28,740 --> 00:00:34,859
Over the past few years, we have seen
organizations adopt LLMs through chatbots,

8
00:00:35,680 --> 00:00:38,699
assistants, and content generation tools.

9
00:00:39,199 --> 00:00:44,159
But moving from a demo to a
production-grade system introduces

10
00:00:44,519 --> 00:00:46,599
a very different set of challenges.

11
00:00:47,280 --> 00:00:52,850
The focus of today's talk is not
just what LLMs can do, it's how we

12
00:00:52,850 --> 00:01:00,639
can architect that allow them to
operate reliably, safely, and at scale

13
00:01:01,139 --> 00:01:02,239
A little bit about me.

14
00:01:02,349 --> 00:01:04,319
My name is Mastul Hassan Choudhury.

15
00:01:04,789 --> 00:01:06,859
I'm a staff product manager at Walmart.

16
00:01:07,329 --> 00:01:12,279
I've spent several years building
enterprise products across retail

17
00:01:12,279 --> 00:01:17,609
operations, supply chain fulfillment,
and also AI-enabled systems.

18
00:01:17,679 --> 00:01:21,989
Over the course of my career, I have
worked on large-scale operational

19
00:01:22,039 --> 00:01:26,809
platforms, user onboarding systems,
mobile commerce solutions, and most

20
00:01:26,809 --> 00:01:29,019
recently, GenAI-powered products.

21
00:01:29,939 --> 00:01:35,789
What I've learned is that technology
succeeds when it fits naturally

22
00:01:35,799 --> 00:01:38,139
into the operational workflows.

23
00:01:38,709 --> 00:01:44,009
The perspective heavily influences the
architecture that I will share today

24
00:01:44,509 --> 00:01:51,469
Now, many organizations have adopted
LLMs, but most deployments stop short

25
00:01:51,469 --> 00:01:54,069
of delivering operational values.

26
00:01:54,129 --> 00:01:54,639
Why?

27
00:01:55,139 --> 00:02:01,189
Because production environments
demand far more intelligent responses.

28
00:02:01,619 --> 00:02:06,919
They require reliability, they
require consistency, and they require

29
00:02:07,139 --> 00:02:10,019
integration into real business processes.

30
00:02:10,519 --> 00:02:15,439
The challenge is no longer whether
LLMs can answer a question.

31
00:02:15,909 --> 00:02:21,129
The challenge is whether it can support
thousands of business decisions every

32
00:02:21,129 --> 00:02:27,429
day while meeting cost, latency,
governance, and stability requirements.

33
00:02:28,039 --> 00:02:29,859
That's the gap we are trying to solve

34
00:02:30,359 --> 00:02:36,609
Now, I believe the most effective
way to think about LLM agents is as

35
00:02:36,639 --> 00:02:42,429
co-pilots, not as replacements for
people, not autonomous decision-makers,

36
00:02:42,769 --> 00:02:46,439
but systems that augment human expertise.

37
00:02:46,939 --> 00:02:51,709
A co-pilot gathers information,
evaluate options, highlight tasks,

38
00:02:52,049 --> 00:02:53,769
and surfaces recommendation.

39
00:02:54,359 --> 00:02:56,249
Humans still own the judgment.

40
00:02:56,839 --> 00:02:59,129
Humans still own accountability.

41
00:02:59,529 --> 00:03:06,689
The agent simply helps them
process complexity faster and more

42
00:03:06,689 --> 00:03:12,059
consistently To make this concept
concrete, let's use forecasting and

43
00:03:12,059 --> 00:03:14,339
operational planning as an example.

44
00:03:14,899 --> 00:03:19,379
Now, forecasting is a great test
bed because it combines structured

45
00:03:19,529 --> 00:03:21,179
and unstructured information.

46
00:03:21,609 --> 00:03:25,759
So we have demand signals, we
have operational matrices, we

47
00:03:25,759 --> 00:03:30,189
have external events, market
conditions, human expertise.

48
00:03:30,479 --> 00:03:34,679
This is exactly the type of
environment where agents provide value.

49
00:03:35,249 --> 00:03:39,569
And while we're using forecasting
as an example, the same architecture

50
00:03:39,569 --> 00:03:43,949
applies across supply chain,
capacity planning, risk management,

51
00:03:44,179 --> 00:03:47,049
operations, and many other domains

52
00:03:47,549 --> 00:03:52,819
Now, when organizations start
AI initiatives, they often

53
00:03:52,819 --> 00:03:54,919
focus on the model itself.

54
00:03:55,459 --> 00:03:58,749
I believe the architecture
is far more important.

55
00:03:59,249 --> 00:04:03,889
This framework that I'm presenting
over here consists of three layers.

56
00:04:04,749 --> 00:04:10,929
We have a signal ag-aggregation layer,
we have a LLM agent reasoning layer,

57
00:04:11,429 --> 00:04:14,689
and we have a human interaction layer.

58
00:04:15,329 --> 00:04:21,969
Each layer has a distinct responsibility,
and each can evolve independently.

59
00:04:22,549 --> 00:04:27,649
The separation creates resilience
and makes production deployment

60
00:04:27,909 --> 00:04:34,679
significantly ea-easier Now let's talk
about these three layers separately.

61
00:04:35,179 --> 00:04:37,989
The first is the signal aggregation layer.

62
00:04:38,489 --> 00:04:40,549
Everything begins with context.

63
00:04:41,099 --> 00:04:44,859
Now, the signal aggregation layer
continuously collects information

64
00:04:45,129 --> 00:04:50,049
from multiple sources: structured
data such as transactions, forecasts,

65
00:04:50,359 --> 00:04:54,439
operational metrics, and also
unstructured information such as

66
00:04:54,469 --> 00:04:56,919
documents, reports, logs, communications.

67
00:04:57,469 --> 00:05:02,889
The goal is to create a unified,
queryable context layer.

68
00:05:03,839 --> 00:05:08,799
Without high-quality context, no
amount of model sophistication will

69
00:05:08,799 --> 00:05:11,719
be able to produce reliable decisions.

70
00:05:12,219 --> 00:05:17,029
The second layer is the
LLM agent reasoning layer.

71
00:05:17,669 --> 00:05:22,559
Once the context is assembled in the
first layer, the reasoning begins.

72
00:05:22,859 --> 00:05:28,469
This is where the LLM evaluates
information, generates forecasts, detects

73
00:05:28,499 --> 00:05:31,569
anom-anomalies, and recommends action.

74
00:05:32,069 --> 00:05:35,689
Importantly, the output
is not just an answer.

75
00:05:36,099 --> 00:05:37,539
It includes rationale.

76
00:05:38,059 --> 00:05:41,159
It explains why a recommendation was made.

77
00:05:42,019 --> 00:05:49,169
This explainability is critical for trust
and governance and also for adoption.

78
00:05:49,529 --> 00:05:53,779
If users cannot understand the
recommendation, they won't act

79
00:05:53,779 --> 00:05:58,239
on it And the last layer is
the human interaction layer.

80
00:05:59,079 --> 00:06:02,169
This is where the humans
interact with the system.

81
00:06:02,739 --> 00:06:06,959
Users ask questions, explore
various scenarios, validate

82
00:06:06,979 --> 00:06:08,969
assumptions, and provide feedback.

83
00:06:09,549 --> 00:06:15,329
The interaction layer transforms
the system from a black box into

84
00:06:15,369 --> 00:06:18,249
a collaborative decision partner.

85
00:06:18,989 --> 00:06:25,799
This is where trust is built, and trust
is often the deciding factor between

86
00:06:25,829 --> 00:06:31,299
AI adoption and AI rejection Now let's
talk about some of the production

87
00:06:31,519 --> 00:06:34,479
realities, some of the hard problems.

88
00:06:35,399 --> 00:06:41,189
For example, b-building an architecture is
one thing, but operating it in production

89
00:06:41,299 --> 00:06:43,299
is a completely different ball game.

90
00:06:44,259 --> 00:06:46,499
Four challenges consistently appear.

91
00:06:47,049 --> 00:06:48,199
First, we have hal-hallucinations.

92
00:06:48,699 --> 00:06:50,949
Second, decision consistency.

93
00:06:51,759 --> 00:06:55,039
We have latency issues,
and then we have cost.

94
00:06:55,429 --> 00:06:59,759
These issues won't disappear
simply because the model

95
00:06:59,759 --> 00:07:01,609
performs well in testing.

96
00:07:02,059 --> 00:07:06,559
Production success requires
deliberate engineering choices

97
00:07:06,949 --> 00:07:10,219
to manage all four simultaneously

98
00:07:10,719 --> 00:07:12,449
Now how to solve these problems?

99
00:07:12,969 --> 00:07:18,509
The s-single most important technique
for reducing hallucination is grounding.

100
00:07:19,399 --> 00:07:23,899
Agents should not rely
solely on model knowledge.

101
00:07:24,179 --> 00:07:27,009
They should operate using enterprise data.

102
00:07:27,769 --> 00:07:32,549
Retrieval augmentation-- augmented
generation, structured queries,

103
00:07:32,929 --> 00:07:37,529
and authoritative internal sources
dramatically improve reliability.

104
00:07:37,989 --> 00:07:40,809
Grounding is not a
one-time implementation.

105
00:07:41,239 --> 00:07:47,189
It becomes an ongoing operational
discipline focused on freshness, quality,

106
00:07:47,719 --> 00:07:53,709
and monitoring Now many business decisions
cannot be solved with a single prompt.

107
00:07:54,089 --> 00:07:58,209
Instead, they require
multi-step reasoning steps.

108
00:07:59,059 --> 00:08:05,299
First, retrieve context, then create
a plan, then execute tools, and

109
00:08:05,299 --> 00:08:07,149
finally synthesize the results.

110
00:08:07,539 --> 00:08:12,289
This orchestration process
resembles how human analysts work.

111
00:08:12,689 --> 00:08:19,459
The difference is that agents can execute
these steps continuously and at scale

112
00:08:19,959 --> 00:08:23,309
One of the biggest mistakes
organizations make is trying

113
00:08:23,319 --> 00:08:25,239
to replace existing systems.

114
00:08:25,739 --> 00:08:29,089
A better strategy is additive integration.

115
00:08:29,919 --> 00:08:34,459
Use adaptive layers around
existing systems, deploy in shadow

116
00:08:34,459 --> 00:08:38,569
mode, and maintain deterministic
fall, fallback mechanism.

117
00:08:38,939 --> 00:08:44,539
This allows organization to innovate while
also preserving operational stability.

118
00:08:45,069 --> 00:08:47,709
The goal is not evo-evo-evolution.

119
00:08:48,149 --> 00:08:51,219
The goal is evolution and not disruption

120
00:08:51,719 --> 00:08:55,309
This slide captures the core
philosophy of the presentation.

121
00:08:55,929 --> 00:09:01,529
Agents handle monitoring, synthesis,
pattern detection, scenario

122
00:09:01,529 --> 00:09:03,179
generation, and summarization.

123
00:09:03,679 --> 00:09:05,389
Humans still retain judgment.

124
00:09:05,719 --> 00:09:07,949
Humans still retain context.

125
00:09:08,259 --> 00:09:10,429
Humans retain accountability.

126
00:09:10,749 --> 00:09:13,609
The future is not human versus AI.

127
00:09:14,089 --> 00:09:16,669
The future is human plus AI

128
00:09:17,169 --> 00:09:23,629
Now, most AI initiatives fail because they
jump quickly from prototype to production.

129
00:09:24,049 --> 00:09:26,959
A better path is progressive maturity.

130
00:09:27,359 --> 00:09:32,739
Start with focused prototype, move
to shadow deployment, introduce

131
00:09:32,839 --> 00:09:37,599
human-in-the-loop validation, then
scale with monitoring, governance,

132
00:09:37,829 --> 00:09:39,569
and continuous evaluation.

133
00:09:40,359 --> 00:09:45,069
This approach reduces risk
while also increase, increasing

134
00:09:45,329 --> 00:09:48,209
organizational confi-confidence.

135
00:09:48,709 --> 00:09:51,529
Now, key takeaways for practitioners.

136
00:09:51,849 --> 00:09:55,739
If you remember only four things
from today, remember these.

137
00:09:56,239 --> 00:09:59,769
First, architecture comes before models.

138
00:10:00,529 --> 00:10:03,999
Second, ground everything
in enterprise data.

139
00:10:04,869 --> 00:10:10,829
Third, integrate additively rather
than replacing existing systems.

140
00:10:11,189 --> 00:10:16,569
And fourth, continuously measure
performance across accuracy,

141
00:10:17,009 --> 00:10:19,669
latency, cost, and human trust.

142
00:10:20,039 --> 00:10:24,609
These principles are what separate
successful production deployment

143
00:10:24,999 --> 00:10:27,889
from impressive demonstrations.

144
00:10:28,389 --> 00:10:30,219
So thank you for your time.

145
00:10:30,469 --> 00:10:34,979
I hope this framework provides
a practical perspective on how

146
00:10:35,669 --> 00:10:40,689
your organization can move beyond
experimentation and build scalable AI

147
00:10:40,699 --> 00:10:43,729
systems that create real business value.

